Comment: trainerheidi said "It's time to stop living in a fantasy world!

Goals aren't achieved without hard work. And it doesn't happen overnight. If you would ask people that have companies, killer bodies and everything else you look up to, they would tell you that it took them months, years, decades even. And you know what was the component to all of that? CONSISTENCY. Simple, yet necessary element. 
So, as we're approaching "New Years resolution" promises, make sure they're not fake. Meaning, you will follow through this wish and goal that you've set for yourself. 
If you want to become a business owner, make sure that you DAILY work overtime for that business. 
If you want to achieve your best physique yet, make sure that you DAILY watch your diet and exercise and get enough sleep. 
If you want to save money, make sure you DAILY make financially smart decisions and save every penny you can. 
If you want to become a better person, make sure you DAILY work on yourself, meditate, read, pray. 
You see? Only commitment DAILY will help you to achieve all of your goals. And when it gets tough, not "if" but "when" because it WILL get tough, because we're lazy creatures by the definition, remember WHY you're doing this and push through it. 
That's the one and ONLY way how you'll achieve every single goal in your life."

Comment: fd_gallery said "British by birth, she was a granddaughter of both Queen Victoria and Tsar Alexander II of Russia. After refusing a proposal from her cousin, the future King George V, she was pushed in 1893 by her mother to marry a Balkan Crown Prince. She was immensely popular with the people in her husband's homeland, and was known for her whimsical style of dress and for her fantastic jewels. In 1914, her husband became King, and she Queen, though with the outbreak of the Great War, and facing the occupation by her cousin the German Kaiser's troops, she deposited the entirety of her jewel collection, along with gold reserves which consisted of two railway carloads of gold, with her Romanov relatives in Russia for safekeeping. By the end of the war however, the Russian Tsar was dethroned and the new government refused to return her valuables. To aid her exiled family members who had lost their titles and fortunes, she purchased many of their jewels to replace her own, including those of her sister Victoria Melita, herself a Russian Grand Duchess, and a daughter in law of the formidable Grand Duchess Vladimir. In 1922, in anticipation of her own postponed coronation, her husband showered her with new jewels, including a valuable Cartier diamond sautoir suspending an egg sized sapphire weighing 476.68 carats and a crown made in the Art Nouveau Style by the Parisian firm Falize. She is pictured here wearing a pair of natural pearl drop earrings, which were inherited by her son and given to his mistress. Upon the mistress' death in 1977, the pearls were forgotten and languished in a desk drawer for 35 years, until they were sold by an English country house in 2012, fetching $2,500,000. They were purchased by a Qatari Prince who had them reset by the jeweler JAR....so who was their original owner? Name that Queen! #FD_triviaTuesday #JARjewels"
